SIMPLE: machinery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Machinery
<hw>Ma*chin"er*y</hw> <pr>(m⟦adot⟧*sh⟦emac⟧n"⟦etil⟧r*⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Machine</er>: cf. F.
<ets>machinerie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Machines, in general, or
collectively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The working parts of a machine, engine, or
instrument; <as>as, the <ex>machinery</ex> of a watch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The supernatural means by which the action of a
poetic or fictitious work is carried on and brought to a catastrophe; in
an extended sense, the contrivances by which the crises and conclusion
of a fictitious narrative, in prose or verse, are effected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>machinery</qex>, madam, is a term invented by the
critics, to signify that part which the deities, angels, or demons, are
made to act in a poem.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The means and appliances by which anything is kept
in action or a desired result is obtained; a complex system of parts
adapted to a purpose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An indispensable part of the <qex>machinery</qex> of state.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The delicate inflexional <qex>machinery</qex> of the Aryan
languages.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor (The Alphabet).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine screw</ent>⟦br⟧
